    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-06-16T20:02:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-06-16T20:02:00-05:00" n="87"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d87">
                <head>87. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Lebanon</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d87fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 783A.00/6–1658. Top Secret; <gloss target="#t_Niact1">Niact</gloss>;
                        Limit Distribution. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_RSW1"
                            >Rockwell</persName> and cleared by <persName corresp="#p_WFO1"
                            >Wilcox</persName> in draft and by <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName>. Repeated to London and <gloss target="#t_USUN1"
                            >USUN</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1958-06-16T21:02:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 16, 1958—9:02 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4814. We are disturbed at tenor of <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss>
                        4756.<note n="2" xml:id="d87fn2">
                        <ref target="#d85">Document 85</ref>.</note> We do not intend allied forces
                    be used in Lebanon unless factors specified <gloss target="#t_Deptel1"
                        >Deptel</gloss> 4271<note n="3" xml:id="d87fn3">
                        <ref target="#d31">Document 31</ref>.</note> are present. You should
                    certainly disabuse <persName corresp="#p_CC7">Chamoun</persName> of thought that
                    allied landings would be for purpose of facilitating removal of General
                        <persName corresp="#p_CGF2">Chehab</persName>. We have come to believe it is
                    almost a sine qua non that Lebanon have had full recourse to orderly processes
                    of <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> before finally requesting and receiving
                    friendly assistance (<gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 4790).<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d87fn4">
                        <ref target="#d82">Document 82</ref>.</note> This process would naturally
                    take several days once decision have further recourse to <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                        >UN</gloss> taken. If Lebanese security requirements demand removal of
                        <persName corresp="#p_CGF2">Chehab</persName> at once this obviously cannot
                    be done within context prior allied landing which, if it took place, would be
                    aftermath of further <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> consideration of matter
                    at Lebanese initiative.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>. First contingent of US forces, around 1,
                    600 men, could arrive within 8–12 hours if US should decide to provide
                    assistance to <gloss target="#t_GOL1">GOL</gloss>. Remainder of US forces could
                    arrive within 24 hours of same decision. You should not convey this information
                    to <persName corresp="#p_CC7">Chamoun</persName> at this time.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
